{"title_page": "Jon Moss", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=January 2020}}\n{{About|the drummer|the association football referee|Jonathan Moss (referee)}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Jon Moss\n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| image               = JonMoss2011.jpg\n| caption             = Moss (left) playing with [[Bob Weston (guitarist)|Bob Weston]] on \"Spring Heeled Jack\" for a blues night jamming session.\n| birth_name          = Jonathan Aubrey Moss\n| alias               = \n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=y|1957|9|11}}\n| genre               = {{flatlist|\n* [[Punk rock]]\n* [[New wave music|new wave]]\n* [[pop rock]]\n}} \n| occupation          = \n| instrument          = \n| years_active        = 1976\u2013present\n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = {{flatlist|\n* [[London (punk band)|London]]\n* [[The Nipple Erectors|The Nips]]\n* [[The Damned (band)|The Damned]]\n* [[Adam and the Ants|Adam & The Ants]]\n* [[Culture Club]]\n}}\n| website             =  \n}}\n\n'''Jonathan Aubrey Moss''' (born 11 September 1957) is an English drummer, best known as a member of the 1980s new wave group [[Culture Club]]. He has also played with other bands, including [[London (punk band)|London]], [[The Nipple Erectors|The Nips]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.punk77.co.uk/groups/nippleerectorsshanneinterview.htm |title=The Nipple Erectors \u2013 Shannne Bradley Interview |publisher=Punk77.co.uk |date=26 August 2001 |accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref> [[The Damned (band)|The Damned]] and [[Adam and the Ants|Adam & The Ants]].\n\n==Early life==\nMoss was born in Clapham Jewish Boys Home at [[Wandsworth]], [[South London]], and was adopted when six months old by Rosetta (n\u00e9e Goldsmith, b. 1929) and Lionel Moss (b. 1927, d. 1999),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://search.ancestry.com/cgi-bin/sse.dll?gl=ROOT_CATEGORY&rank=1&new=1&so=3&MSAV=0&msT=1&gss=ms_r_f-2_s&gsfn=Jonathan+Aubrey&gsln=Moss&msbdy=1957&msfng0=Lionel&msfns0=Moss&uidh=000&mssng0=Barbara&mssns0=Denton+Savage&msbng0=David&msbns0=Moss |title=Jonathan Aubrey Moss |publisher=Search.ancestry.com |accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref> an [[Social structure of Britain#Upper middle class|upper-middle-class]] couple of Jewish ancestry. His father owned a clothing store called ''Alkit'', located at [[Cambridge Circus, London|Cambridge Circus]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Village |first=Hampstead |url=http://hampsteadvillagevoice.blogspot.com/2009_05_01_archive.html |title=Hampstead Village Voice Blog..Blagg...whatever you fancy!: May 2009 |publisher=Hampsteadvillagevoice.blogspot.com |date=13 May 2009 |accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.curiousfox.com/uk/mbprof2.lasso?eid=147765&-nothing |title=Fanny COHEN nee MOSS London |publisher=Curiousfox.com |accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref> He grew up in [[Hampstead]], attending [[Arnold House School]] (1962\u20131970) and [[Highgate School]] (1970\u20131975).\n\nDuring Moss's childhood, music began to have an important role in his life, and he would play well-known songs on his family's piano. His elder brother, David, was drummer in a school band and had a Wayward drum kit, which Jon borrowed to start playing when 13 years old.<ref name=\"multinet.no\">[http://www.multinet.no/~jonarne/Hjemmesia/.../culture_club.htm ]{{dead link|date=June 2013}}</ref>\n\nAt [[Highgate School]], Moss developed a fascination for sports, especially boxing, but he did not want a professional sporting career. It was also at Highgate that he formed his first band, Pig Williams, along with his friend [[Nick Feldman]] (who would later become a member and co-founder of [[Wang Chung (band)|Wang Chung]]). Together they performed at several school events. After finishing high school, Jon held various jobs, including working at his father's clothing store, as a cake salesman and as a [[sound engineer]] at [[Marquee Club|Marquee Studios]]. In spite of regarding a college graduation as a waste of time, he briefly considered the idea of studying [[Greek language|Greek]] at the [[University of Cambridge]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture-club.co.uk/content/jon_index.htm |title=Official Culture Club Website |publisher=Culture-club.co.uk |accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Musical career==\n===Beginning (1976\u201380)===\nAlongside his friend [[Riff Regan]], Moss joined the [[Punk rock|punk]] band [[London (punk band)|London]] in 1976,<ref>[https://www.allmusic.com/artist/london-p18987/biography allmusic.com biography on ''London'']</ref><ref name=\"Rimmer\">Rimmer, Dave (1985) \"Like Punk Never Happened,\" Faber and Faber, {{ISBN|978-0-571-13739-8}}, p. 40-42</ref><ref name=\"Kasper de Graaf & Malcolm Garrett\">Kasper de Graaf & Malcolm Garrett (1983) \"When Cameras Go Crazy \u2013 Culture Club,\" Virgin Books, {{ISBN|0-907080-85-5}}, p. 62</ref> after being tried out as a drummer with [[The Clash]]; later, he said \"The mix of personalities didn't work. Their attitudes were too different to mine.\"<ref name=\"Kasper de Graaf & Malcolm Garrett\"/> London released a single entitled \"Everyone's a Winner\", and were managed by [[Simon Napier-Bell]]. Eventually they recorded two singles, a four-track EP and an album for [[MCA Records]] in 1977.<ref name=\"Napier-Bell\">Napier-Bell, Simon (2001) \"Black Vinyl White Powder,\" Ebury Press, {{ISBN|978-0-09-186992-2}}, p. 163</ref> Following this, Moss went on tour with established punk group [[The Stranglers]], and the band got a record deal.\n\nSoon afterward, Moss began drumming with [[The Damned (band)|The Damned]], replacing [[Rat Scabies]] who had quit the band. He made the final decision to join them, after he was injured in a car crash on New Year's Eve 1977, when he suffered fractures to his face (his injuries required 250 stitches), resulting in a broken nose and a week's hospital stay.  Along with the Damned's guitarist, 'Lu' Edmonds, he left the Damned to form new wave band the Edge, along with bassist/vocalist Glyn Havard (formerly of New Age pioneers, Jade Warrior) and keyboardist Gavin Povey (later of Albert Lee's band, Hogan's Heroes).  The Edge toured Britain with the Skids and the Yachts, as well as morphing into backing bands for Kirsty McColl and Jane Aire, also finding time to beat the Stranglers' audience record at one of London's most popular venues of the time, the Nashville.  Following a successful support slot at the Stranglers' Battersea Park concert, the band was invited to try out for the job of Peter Gabriel's new backing band, but turned the opportunity down.  After just over a year, the Edge broke up, but not before Moss had completed an Exegesis program, a new age 'therapy' that loosely speaking, engendered the break down and consequent rebuilding of participants' psychological states.  Mike Oldfield was another famous recipient of this treatment.<ref name=\"multinet.no\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www-personal.umich.edu/~mhuey/damned/ |title=Chapter 2: The Bubble Bursts |publisher=Personal.umich.edu |date=24 September 1957 |accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe played with [[Adam and the Ants]], before their commercial success, on their third single [[Dirk Wears White Sox|\"Cartrouble\"]] and its b-side \"Kick!\". At the time Moss was with a group called Jane Aire & The Belvederes, and under contract with that band: therefore he was credited on the original single under the pseudonym \"Terry 1 & 2\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.adam-ant.net/Cartrouble.html|last=Ant|first=Adam|title=Cartrouble|website=Adam-Ant.net|publisher=Universal Music Publishing Group.}}</ref> He has since been credited under his real name on reissues of the tracks, starting with the 1984 CBS/Epic reissue of ''[[Dirk Wears White Sox]]''.\n\n===Culture Club \u2013 early times (1981\u201386)===\nMoss was advised by a friend that [[Boy George]] was looking for a drummer for his band. When he became a member of the band\u2014which was originally called in Praise of Lemmings\u2014he suggested changing the name of the group to [[Culture Club]], in reference to the various [[Multiculturalism|ethnic background]]s of the members.\n\nIn 1985, whilst still performing with Culture Club, he produced some tracks for the band Woyeyeh.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pc-pdx.com/bands/Jon-Moss |title=JON MOSS &#124; Shows + Photos + Biography + More &#124; Portland Show-Guide |publisher=Pc-pdx.com |accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref>\n[[File:7inch5inch ubt.jpeg|right|thumb| Moss on a [[Move Away]] Culture Club 7\" vinyl]]\n\n===Other works and Culture Club reunion (1987\u20132002)===\nAfter Culture Club broke up in 1986, Moss released a single entitled \"Jump to It\" with the group Heartbeat UK, which he also produced.\n\nIn 1989, under the name Rubberman, Moss released one [[white label]] of an [[acid house]] [[instrumental]] track. Boy George used that backing track to create his own song \"After the Love\", which was released as a single by [[Jesus Loves You (band)|Jesus Loves You]].\n\nDuring 1991 and 1992 Moss was involved in another group, [[Promised Land (band)|Promised Land]], with his schoolfriend Nick Feldman. The two released two singles, \"Something in the Air\" and \"Circle in the Square\", and also a self-titled album.\n\nIn 1995 he met Sebastian Wocker, vocalist of the [[indie pop|indie]] band Yeah, and soon joined them. For two years the group played several concerts on the London circuit, made various television appearances and filmed one video Engerland in 1997 at the former home of [[Hendon F.C.]]. Their last concert was at [[Camden Underworld|The Underworld]] in [[Camden Town]] in 1998.\n\nMoss was a part of the Culture Club reformation between 1998 and 2002.\n\n===Charities, b-side projects (2003\u201310)===\nFrom 2003 to 2005 Moss joined several [[punk rock]] and rock bands, among them Fassbender, DanMingo and [[Dirth]]. In July 2005 he played drums on the charity single \"People I Don't Know Are Trying to Kill Me\", written by the journalist [[Neil McCormick]], to help the families of the victims of the [[7 July 2005 London bombings|terrorist bombings in London]].<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/arts/main.jhtml?xml=/arts/2005/07/19/bmneil19.xml \"Bono told me: 'Your song needs to be heard now'\"]. Daily Telegraph (19 July 2005). Retrieved 9 July 2011.</ref> He has also performed and recorded with the London-based singer and songwriter Anca.\n\nIn 2006 Moss, [[Mikey Craig]] and [[Phil Pickett]] tried to launch Culture Club on a new tour with another lead singer, as George and [[Roy Hay (musician)|Roy Hay]] had declined to tour.<ref>[[Culture Club#Reunions]]</ref> A UK tour was announced for December 2006, but was postponed to give the new line-up time to finish recording their album. Without official press statements, band manager Tony Gordon said in 2007 that the project was \"on hold\", while Jon stated that the project was shelved.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/music/news/2006-11-02-culture-club-clash_x.htm |title=Boy George's ex-bandmates slam singer |work=USA Today |date=2 November 2006 |accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nMoss was interviewed in May 2009 by the ''Hampstead Village Voice'' about his early life and career.\n\nIn 2010 he also played a few gigs with the band Plastic Heroes.\n\n===Culture Club \u2013 Reunion (2011\u2013present)===\nJon Moss did not appear at Culture Club's concerts in Dubai and Sydney in December 2011, due to a back injury which required surgery.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://shapersofthe80s.com/2012/01/02/2012 |title=2012 \u27a4 Moss misses Culture Club's new dawn in Australia &#124; \u27a2\u27a2 Shapers of the 80s \u27a3\u27a3 |publisher=Shapersofthe80s.com |date=2 January 2012 |accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref> Despite rumours that the reunion project had been shelved, Boy George said in an interview with [[Danny Baker]] on [[BBC Radio 5 Live|BBC Radio 5]]\u2014which aired in March 2012\u2014that their new album would be released in 2013, but did not mention any date for a tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gaystarnews.com/article/boy-george-gets-black-eye-nightclub-attack050412 |title=Boy George gets black eye in nightclub attack |publisher=Gay Star News |date=5 April 2012 |accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, Moss had been drumming with Mad Dog Bites, alongside Martin French (vocals), Godfrey Old (harmonica), Peter Noone (bass) and Conrad Blakemore (guitar).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nJEljecSCgo |title=Mad Dog Bites \u2013 Talking 'Bout You \u2013 Hampstead Xmas Festival 2012 |via=YouTube |date=5 January 2013 |accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref> Former [[Fleetwood Mac]] member [[Bob Weston (guitarist)|Bob Weston]] was their guitarist until his death in January 2012.\n\nIn the [[Red Nose Day 2013|Red Nose Day '13]] at [[Whiteleys]], Moss sang with [[Rock Choir|The Rock Choir]], helping them to fundraise for [[Comic Relief]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.christinalaroque.com/2013/03/rock-choir-and-christina-support-red-nose-day/?info=page&replytocom=2 |title=Rock Choir and Christina support Red Nose Day! |publisher=Christinalaroque.com |date=11 March 2013 |accessdate=17 June 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512225604/http://www.christinalaroque.com/2013/03/rock-choir-and-christina-support-red-nose-day/?info=page&replytocom=2 |archivedate=12 May 2014  }}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Culture Club began recording a new album, originally named ''Tribes''. The ''Tribes'' sessions were recorded in Spain and documented in the film ''From Karma to Calamity'' which aired on [[BBC Four]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b054v27d|title=BBC Four \u2013 Boy George and Culture Club: Karma to Calamity|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=30 October 2018}}</ref> In July 2018, it was announced that the sessions had been reworked as ''Life'', and was to be released on 26 October 2018<ref name=\"SDE\"/> credited to \"[[Boy George]] and Culture Club\". Lead single ''Let Somebody Love You'' was credited to all four original members of the group, but Moss was not credited as song writer on the title track. A third and final single, a limited edition issue of ''Runaway Train'' which was re-recorded as a duet with [[Gladys Knight]] and released for [[Record Store Day]] 2019 was written by the group with long-time collaborator [[John Themis]].\n\nIn early 2018 Moss formed pop band Ridiculous together with singer-songwriter Sebastian Wocker, bassist Peter Noone and film score composer Erran Baron Cohen. The band's debut performance took place at The Dublin Castle, Camden, London on 13 June 2018.\n\nCulture Club toured the US and Europe from June to December 2018 in support of their [[Life (Boy George and Culture Club album)|Life]] album, along with supporting acts [[The B-52s]], [[Tom Bailey (musician)|Tom Bailey]] (formerly of [[The Thompson Twins]]) and [[Belinda Carlisle]] (Europe dates only). Jon Moss was originally part of the line-up, but left after the US leg of the tour. \n\nIn December 2019, Moss filed a writ at London\u2019s High Court naming the band trio as defendants. Moss' lawyers say he was told to \u201ctake a break\u201d by manager [[Paul Kemsley]], demanding nearly \u00a3200,000 in missing payments and a share of profits.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twnews.co.uk/gb-news/boy-george-sued-by-ex-lover-and-drummer-jon-moss-after-he-booted-him-out-of-culture-club |title=Boy George sued by ex-lover and drummer Jon Moss after he booted him out of Culture Club |publisher=TWNEWS|accessdate=15 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nJon Moss has three children with his former wife Barbara Savage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/woman/celeb-news/did-you-really-want-to-hurt-each-other-26260451.html|title=Did you really want to hurt each other? |work=The Irish Independent|access-date=1 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/boy-georges-culture-club-finally-3677610|title=Boy George's Culture Club finally reunited after 15 years split|last=Martin|first=Gavin|date=12 June 2014|work=mirror|access-date=1 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nMoss had a relationship with Boy George during the height of Culture Club's popularity, although it was not public knowledge at the time.<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1995/11/15/boy-george-the-man/59944def-e309-4cfc-828d-449410acd5f4/</ref><ref>https://www.express.co.uk/celebrity-news/173812/Boy-George-regrets-publicly-airing-Moss-romance</ref> Their affair came to an end in 1986;<ref>https://www.msn.com/en-gb/entertainment/music/boy-georges-ex-jon-moss-leaves-culture-club/ar-BBP3pNK</ref> it was portrayed in ''[[Worried About the Boy]]'', a [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]] shown on [[BBC Two|BBC2]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Worried About the Boy (TV Movie 2010)|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1597178/plotsummary?ref_=tt_ov_pl|accessdate=1 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|1588024}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|\nbefore=[[David Barbarossa|Dave Barbe]] | title=[[Adam and the Ants]] drummer | years=1980 | after=Terry Lee Miall<br>&<br>[[Chris Hughes (musician)|Merrick]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Culture Club}}\n{{The Damned}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moss, Jon}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Arnold House School]]\n[[Category:People educated at Highgate School]]\n[[Category:English adoptees]]\n[[Category:LGBT musicians from England]]\n[[Category:English Jews]]\n[[Category:LGBT Jews]]\n[[Category:People from Wandsworth]]\n[[Category:English new wave musicians]]\n[[Category:English punk rock drummers]]\n[[Category:English rock drummers]]\n[[Category:Bisexual men]]\n[[Category:Bisexual musicians]]\n[[Category:The Damned (band) members]]\n[[Category:Culture Club members]]\n[[Category:Jews in punk rock]]\n[[Category:The Nips members]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=January 2020}}\n{{About|the drummer|the association football referee|Jonathan Moss (referee)}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Jon Moss\n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| image               = JonMoss2011.jpg\n| caption             = Moss (left) playing with [[Bob Weston (guitarist)|Bob Weston]] on \"Spring Heeled Jack\" for a blues night jamming session.\n| birth_name          = Jonathan Aubrey Moss\n| alias               = \n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=y|1957|9|11}}\n| genre               = {{flatlist|\n* [[Punk rock]]\n* [[New wave music|new wave]]\n* [[pop rock]]\n}} \n| occupation          = \n| instrument          = \n| years_active        = 1976\u2013present\n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = {{flatlist|\n* [[London (punk band)|London]]\n* [[The Nipple Erectors|The Nips]]\n* [[The Damned (band)|The Damned]]\n* [[Adam and the Ants|Adam & The Ants]]\n* [[Culture Club]]\n}}\n| website             =  \n}}\n\n'''Jonathan Aubrey Moss''' (born 11 September 1957) is an English drummer, best known as a member of the 1980s new wave group [[Culture Club]]. He has also played with other bands, including [[London (punk band)|London]], [[The Nipple Erectors|The Nips]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.punk77.co.uk/groups/nippleerectorsshanneinterview.htm |title=The Nipple Erectors \u2013 Shannne Bradley Interview |publisher=Punk77.co.uk |date=26 August 2001 |accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref> [[The Damned (band)|The Damned]] and [[Adam and the Ants|Adam & The Ants]].\n\n==Early life==\nMoss was born in Clapham Jewish Boys Home at [[Wandsworth]], [[South London]], and was adopted when six months old by Rosetta (n\u00e9e Goldsmith, b. 1929) and Lionel Moss (b. 1927, d. 1999),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://search.ancestry.com/cgi-bin/sse.dll?gl=ROOT_CATEGORY&rank=1&new=1&so=3&MSAV=0&msT=1&gss=ms_r_f-2_s&gsfn=Jonathan+Aubrey&gsln=Moss&msbdy=1957&msfng0=Lionel&msfns0=Moss&uidh=000&mssng0=Barbara&mssns0=Denton+Savage&msbng0=David&msbns0=Moss |title=Jonathan Aubrey Moss |publisher=Search.ancestry.com |accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref> an [[Social structure of Britain#Upper middle class|upper-middle-class]] couple of Jewish ancestry. His father owned a clothing store called ''Alkit'', located at [[Cambridge Circus, London|Cambridge Circus]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Village |first=Hampstead |url=http://hampsteadvillagevoice.blogspot.com/2009_05_01_archive.html |title=Hampstead Village Voice Blog..Blagg...whatever you fancy!: May 2009 |publisher=Hampsteadvillagevoice.blogspot.com |date=13 May 2009 |accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.curiousfox.com/uk/mbprof2.lasso?eid=147765&-nothing |title=Fanny COHEN nee MOSS London |publisher=Curiousfox.com |accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref> He grew up in [[Hampstead]], attending [[Arnold House School]] (1962\u20131970) and [[Highgate School]] (1970\u20131975).\n\nDuring Moss's childhood, music began to have an important role in his life, and he would play well-known songs on his family's piano. His elder brother, David, was drummer in a school band and had a Wayward drum kit, which Jon borrowed to start playing when 13 years old.<ref name=\"multinet.no\">[http://www.multinet.no/~jonarne/Hjemmesia/.../culture_club.htm ]{{dead link|date=June 2013}}</ref>\n\nAt [[Highgate School]], Moss developed a fascination for sports, especially boxing, but he did not want a professional sporting career. It was also at Highgate that he formed his first band, Pig Williams, along with his friend [[Nick Feldman]] (who would later become a member and co-founder of [[Wang Chung (band)|Wang Chung]]). Together they performed at several school events. After finishing high school, Jon held various jobs, including working at his father's clothing store, as a cake salesman and as a [[sound engineer]] at [[Marquee Club|Marquee Studios]]. In spite of regarding a college graduation as a waste of time, he briefly considered the idea of studying [[Greek language|Greek]] at the [[University of Cambridge]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture-club.co.uk/content/jon_index.htm |title=Official Culture Club Website |publisher=Culture-club.co.uk |accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Musical career==\n===Beginning (1976\u201380)===\nAlongside his friend [[Riff Regan]], Moss joined the [[Punk rock|punk]] band [[London (punk band)|London]] in 1976,<ref>[https://www.allmusic.com/artist/london-p18987/biography allmusic.com biography on ''London'']</ref><ref name=\"Rimmer\">Rimmer, Dave (1985) \"Like Punk Never Happened,\" Faber and Faber, {{ISBN|978-0-571-13739-8}}, p. 40-42</ref><ref name=\"Kasper de Graaf & Malcolm Garrett\">Kasper de Graaf & Malcolm Garrett (1983) \"When Cameras Go Crazy \u2013 Culture Club,\" Virgin Books, {{ISBN|0-907080-85-5}}, p. 62</ref> after being tried out as a drummer with [[The Clash]]; later, he said \"The mix of personalities didn't work. Their attitudes were too different to mine.\"<ref name=\"Kasper de Graaf & Malcolm Garrett\"/> London released a single entitled \"Everyone's a Winner\", and were managed by [[Simon Napier-Bell]]. Eventually they recorded two singles, a four-track EP and an album for [[MCA Records]] in 1977.<ref name=\"Napier-Bell\">Napier-Bell, Simon (2001) \"Black Vinyl White Powder,\" Ebury Press, {{ISBN|978-0-09-186992-2}}, p. 163</ref> Following this, Moss went on tour with established punk group [[The Stranglers]], and the band got a record deal.\n\nSoon afterward, Moss began drumming with [[The Damned (band)|The Damned]], replacing [[Rat Scabies]] who had quit the band. He made the final decision to join them, after he was injured in a car crash on New Year's Eve 1977, when he suffered fractures to his face (his injuries required 250 stitches), resulting in a broken nose and a week's hospital stay.  Along with the Damned's guitarist, 'Lu' Edmonds, he left the Damned to form new wave band the Edge, along with bassist/vocalist Glyn Havard (formerly of New Age pioneers, Jade Warrior) and keyboardist Gavin Povey (later of Albert Lee's band, Hogan's Heroes).  The Edge toured Britain with the Skids and the Yachts, as well as morphing into backing bands for Kirsty McColl and Jane Aire, also finding time to beat the Stranglers' audience record at one of London's most popular venues of the time, the Nashville.  Following a successful support slot at the Stranglers' Battersea Park concert, the band was invited to try out for the job of Peter Gabriel's new backing band, but turned the opportunity down.  After just over a year, the Edge broke up, but not before Moss had completed an Exegesis program, a new age 'therapy' that loosely speaking, engendered the break down and consequent rebuilding of participants' psychological states.  Mike Oldfield was another famous recipient of this treatment.<ref name=\"multinet.no\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www-personal.umich.edu/~mhuey/damned/ |title=Chapter 2: The Bubble Bursts |publisher=Personal.umich.edu |date=24 September 1957 |accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe played with [[Adam and the Ants]], before their commercial success, on their third single [[Dirk Wears White Sox|\"Cartrouble\"]] and its b-side \"Kick!\". At the time Moss was with a group called Jane Aire & The Belvederes, and under contract with that band: therefore he was credited on the original single under the pseudonym \"Terry 1 & 2\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.adam-ant.net/Cartrouble.html|last=Ant|first=Adam|title=Cartrouble|website=Adam-Ant.net|publisher=Universal Music Publishing Group.}}</ref> He has since been credited under his real name on reissues of the tracks, starting with the 1984 CBS/Epic reissue of ''[[Dirk Wears White Sox]]''.\n\n===Culture Club \u2013 early times (1981\u201386)===\nMoss was advised by a friend that [[Boy George]] was looking for a drummer for his band. When he became a member of the band\u2014which was originally called in Praise of Lemmings\u2014he suggested changing the name of the group to [[Culture Club]], in reference to the various [[Multiculturalism|ethnic background]]s of the members.\n\nIn 1985, whilst still performing with Culture Club, he produced some tracks for the band Woyeyeh.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pc-pdx.com/bands/Jon-Moss |title=JON MOSS &#124; Shows + Photos + Biography + More &#124; Portland Show-Guide |publisher=Pc-pdx.com |accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref>\n[[File:7inch5inch ubt.jpeg|right|thumb| Moss on a [[Move Away]] Culture Club 7\" vinyl]]\n\n===Other works and Culture Club reunion (1987\u20132002)===\nAfter Culture Club broke up in 1986, Moss released a single entitled \"Jump to It\" with the group Heartbeat UK, which he also produced.\n\nIn 1989, under the name Rubberman, Moss released one [[white label]] of an [[acid house]] [[instrumental]] track. Boy George used that backing track to create his own song \"After the Love\", which was released as a single by [[Jesus Loves You (band)|Jesus Loves You]].\n\nDuring 1991 and 1992 Moss was involved in another group, [[Promised Land (band)|Promised Land]], with his schoolfriend Nick Feldman. The two released two singles, \"Something in the Air\" and \"Circle in the Square\", and also a self-titled album.\n\nIn 1995 he met Sebastian Wocker, vocalist of the [[indie pop|indie]] band Yeah, and soon joined them. For two years the group played several concerts on the London circuit, made various television appearances and filmed one video Engerland in 1997 at the former home of [[Hendon F.C.]]. Their last concert was at [[Camden Underworld|The Underworld]] in [[Camden Town]] in 1998.\n\nMoss was a part of the Culture Club reformation between 1998 and 2002.\n\n===Charities, b-side projects (2003\u201310)===\nFrom 2003 to 2005 Moss joined several [[punk rock]] and rock bands, among them Fassbender, DanMingo and [[Dirth]]. In July 2005 he played drums on the charity single \"People I Don't Know Are Trying to Kill Me\", written by the journalist [[Neil McCormick]], to help the families of the victims of the [[7 July 2005 London bombings|terrorist bombings in London]].<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/arts/main.jhtml?xml=/arts/2005/07/19/bmneil19.xml \"Bono told me: 'Your song needs to be heard now'\"]. Daily Telegraph (19 July 2005). Retrieved 9 July 2011.</ref> He has also performed and recorded with the London-based singer and songwriter Anca.\n\nIn 2006 Moss, [[Mikey Craig]] and [[Phil Pickett]] tried to launch Culture Club on a new tour with another lead singer, as George and [[Roy Hay (musician)|Roy Hay]] had declined to tour.<ref>[[Culture Club#Reunions]]</ref> A UK tour was announced for December 2006, but was postponed to give the new line-up time to finish recording their album. Without official press statements, band manager Tony Gordon said in 2007 that the project was \"on hold\", while Jon stated that the project was shelved.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/music/news/2006-11-02-culture-club-clash_x.htm |title=Boy George's ex-bandmates slam singer |work=USA Today |date=2 November 2006 |accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nMoss was interviewed in May 2009 by the ''Hampstead Village Voice'' about his early life and career.\n\nIn 2010 he also played a few gigs with the band Plastic Heroes.\n\n===Culture Club \u2013 Reunion (2011\u2013present)===\nJon Moss did not appear at Culture Club's concerts in Dubai and Sydney in December 2011, due to a back injury which required surgery.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://shapersofthe80s.com/2012/01/02/2012 |title=2012 \u27a4 Moss misses Culture Club's new dawn in Australia &#124; \u27a2\u27a2 Shapers of the 80s \u27a3\u27a3 |publisher=Shapersofthe80s.com |date=2 January 2012 |accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref> Despite rumours that the reunion project had been shelved, Boy George said in an interview with [[Danny Baker]] on [[BBC Radio 5 Live|BBC Radio 5]]\u2014which aired in March 2012\u2014that their new album would be released in 2013, but did not mention any date for a tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gaystarnews.com/article/boy-george-gets-black-eye-nightclub-attack050412 |title=Boy George gets black eye in nightclub attack |publisher=Gay Star News |date=5 April 2012 |accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, Moss had been drumming with Mad Dog Bites, alongside Martin French (vocals), Godfrey Old (harmonica), Peter Noone (bass) and Conrad Blakemore (guitar).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nJEljecSCgo |title=Mad Dog Bites \u2013 Talking 'Bout You \u2013 Hampstead Xmas Festival 2012 |via=YouTube |date=5 January 2013 |accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref> Former [[Fleetwood Mac]] member [[Bob Weston (guitarist)|Bob Weston]] was their guitarist until his death in January 2012.\n\nIn the [[Red Nose Day 2013|Red Nose Day '13]] at [[Whiteleys]], Moss sang with [[Rock Choir|The Rock Choir]], helping them to fundraise for [[Comic Relief]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.christinalaroque.com/2013/03/rock-choir-and-christina-support-red-nose-day/?info=page&replytocom=2 |title=Rock Choir and Christina support Red Nose Day! |publisher=Christinalaroque.com |date=11 March 2013 |accessdate=17 June 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512225604/http://www.christinalaroque.com/2013/03/rock-choir-and-christina-support-red-nose-day/?info=page&replytocom=2 |archivedate=12 May 2014  }}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Culture Club began recording a new album, originally named ''Tribes''. The ''Tribes'' sessions were recorded in Spain and documented in the film ''From Karma to Calamity'' which aired on [[BBC Four]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b054v27d|title=BBC Four \u2013 Boy George and Culture Club: Karma to Calamity|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=30 October 2018}}</ref> In July 2018, it was announced that the sessions had been reworked as ''Life'', and was to be released on 26 October 2018<ref name=\"SDE\"/> credited to \"[[Boy George]] and Culture Club\". Lead single ''Let Somebody Love You'' was credited to all four original members of the group, but Moss was not credited as song writer on the title track. A third and final single, a limited edition issue of ''Runaway Train'' which was re-recorded as a duet with [[Gladys Knight]] and released for [[Record Store Day]] 2019 was written by the group with long-time collaborator [[John Themis]].\n\nIn early 2018 Moss formed pop band Ridiculous together with singer-songwriter Sebastian Wocker, bassist Peter Noone and film score composer Erran Baron Cohen. The band's debut performance took place at The Dublin Castle, Camden, London on 13 June 2018.\n\nCulture Club toured the US and Europe from June to December 2018 in support of their [[Life (Boy George and Culture Club album)|Life]] album, along with supporting acts [[The B-52s]], [[Tom Bailey (musician)|Tom Bailey]] (formerly of [[The Thompson Twins]]) and [[Belinda Carlisle]] (Europe dates only). Jon Moss was originally part of the line-up, but left after the the US leg of the tour. \n\nIn December 2019, Moss filed a writ at London\u2019s High Court naming the band trio as defendants. Moss' lawyers say he was told to \u201ctake a break\u201d by manager [[Paul Kemsley]], demanding nearly \u00a3200,000 in missing payments and a share of profits.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twnews.co.uk/gb-news/boy-george-sued-by-ex-lover-and-drummer-jon-moss-after-he-booted-him-out-of-culture-club |title=Boy George sued by ex-lover and drummer Jon Moss after he booted him out of Culture Club |publisher=TWNEWS|accessdate=15 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nJon Moss has three children with his former wife Barbara Savage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/woman/celeb-news/did-you-really-want-to-hurt-each-other-26260451.html|title=Did you really want to hurt each other? |work=The Irish Independent|access-date=1 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/boy-georges-culture-club-finally-3677610|title=Boy George's Culture Club finally reunited after 15 years split|last=Martin|first=Gavin|date=12 June 2014|work=mirror|access-date=1 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nMoss had a relationship with Boy George during the height of Culture Club's popularity, although it was not public knowledge at the time.<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1995/11/15/boy-george-the-man/59944def-e309-4cfc-828d-449410acd5f4/</ref><ref>https://www.express.co.uk/celebrity-news/173812/Boy-George-regrets-publicly-airing-Moss-romance</ref> Their affair came to an end in 1986;<ref>https://www.msn.com/en-gb/entertainment/music/boy-georges-ex-jon-moss-leaves-culture-club/ar-BBP3pNK</ref> it was portrayed in ''[[Worried About the Boy]]'', a [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]] shown on [[BBC Two|BBC2]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Worried About the Boy (TV Movie 2010)|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1597178/plotsummary?ref_=tt_ov_pl|accessdate=1 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|1588024}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|\nbefore=[[David Barbarossa|Dave Barbe]] | title=[[Adam and the Ants]] drummer | years=1980 | after=Terry Lee Miall<br>&<br>[[Chris Hughes (musician)|Merrick]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Culture Club}}\n{{The Damned}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moss, Jon}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Arnold House School]]\n[[Category:People educated at Highgate School]]\n[[Category:English adoptees]]\n[[Category:LGBT musicians from England]]\n[[Category:English Jews]]\n[[Category:LGBT Jews]]\n[[Category:People from Wandsworth]]\n[[Category:English new wave musicians]]\n[[Category:English punk rock drummers]]\n[[Category:English rock drummers]]\n[[Category:Bisexual men]]\n[[Category:Bisexual musicians]]\n[[Category:The Damned (band) members]]\n[[Category:Culture Club members]]\n[[Category:Jews in punk rock]]\n[[Category:The Nips members]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jon_Moss"}
